  "market_context": "Intraday price action during London–New York session overlap; price oscillated between expanding highs and lows without breaking structure, forming nested broadening patterns. Analyst identified this during real-time replay of April 9, 2024 price action.",
  "key_observation": "The analyst observed a larger broadening formation on the hourly chart that contained smaller, lower-time-frame broadening formations—each formed by successive sweeps of prior highs/lows and extension of liquidity lines.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: Identified the current trading range (high and low) on the NQ1! hourly chart and noted it was embedded within a higher-time-frame range.",
    "Step 2: Extended trendlines from the most recent high (buy-side liquidity sweep) and low (sell-side liquidity sweep) to the left, connecting prior swept highs and lows to form the outer broadening formation.",
    "Step 3: Within that outer formation, spotted a smaller broadening pattern where a prior high had swept earlier highs and a prior low had swept earlier lows, confirming nested structure.",
    "Step 4: Observed equal highs forming after a sweep of the lower range boundary, indicating likely purge of buy-side liquidity above, consistent with broadening behavior.",
    "Step 5: Concluded price would likely return to the opposite side of the range (higher) since it failed to displace upward and had just swept sell-side liquidity."
  ],
  "outcome": null,
  "lessons": "Broadening formations can nest across timeframes; identifying them requires tracing liquidity sweeps leftward and extending lines from each new extreme. Failure to break out of one side signals likely move to the opposite side, often targeting equal highs/lows as liquidity pools.",
